			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">First of all, a Red Mage is a Mage first and a Melee second. Second, your subclass and main class should agree. They will make you a more powerful character. Mismatched classes will make you more balanced, but the benefit from the sub class is never enough. For example, a WAR/WHM have mismatching class types. The WHM will not add much MP, and the WAR wouldn't get the extra HP and damage from a melee class. A WAR/MNK or a BLM/WHM would be better matches. The WAR/MNK will have increased damage and HP, the BLM/WHM would get more MP as well as some cure spells.
<br />

<br />
1st Question: I don't know for sure, but I would imagine that it wouldn't be good to be a DRG/RDM. You won't be getting much MP, as a DRG has 0. So you would no longer be a full mage. You'd be more of a "worst-case scenario mage", and a pretty poor one at that. A RDM/DRG wouldn't be much better, since a subbed DRG doesn't have the ablity to call a wyvern.
<br />

<br />
2nd Question: Typically, a RDM becomes more mage and less melee at higher levels. Normally, they have three options.
<br />
1) Cast the basic debuffs (Dia, Paralyze, Slow), then start attacking to deal some extra damage, while casting some other debuffs (Poison, Blind, perhaps Bind or Gravity if the monster is constantly hitting the WHM) and renewing any that wear off.
<br />
2) Just chain cast your debuffs, make sure they stick, then rest. If the debuffs wear off, stop resting and recast.
<br />
3) Like option 1, cast the basic debuffs, start attacking, cast the other debuffs. Then, start casting elemental spells in between you attacks and renewal debuffs.
<br />
Of course, in some parties, RDMs are the backup healers, so their strategy will be altered slightly to include this. In any event, at later levels, you will become less melee-based. You won't be doing the damage a WAR would, and people will be liking you for your debuffs and backup healings. In other words... your parties won't expect you to be in the front lines.
<br />

<br />
3rd Question: There are certain spells you really should get. You specialize in debuffs, so get all the debuff spells you can (Dia, Poison, Paralyze, Blind, Bio, Bind, Slow, Silence, Gravity, Sleep, Dia II, Dispel, Bio II, Sleep II, and Haste are the ones I know of, and you need to get the level 2 because level 1 will be inadaquate). Parties also expect you to be a backup healer, so the Cure line would be a good buy. Also, Regen is a good spell, since it helps you out with healing. Blink is a nice spell for fighting solo. By the time you get it, you won't be fighting solo at much (only rare occasions). Elemental spells aren't necessary, (nobody will mistake you for a BLM), although you could get them to help out with solo'ing. I would recommend getting Sneak, Deodorize, and Invisible, if for no other reason than quests and missions. Getting past hordes of ITs will make your experience a lot more fun. Plus, Invisible also works against PCs, so you can hide from your g/f <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" /> . The Bar- spells, I only bought Barsleep and Barpoison, and I've only used them for fighting saplings while alone. The En- spells aren't necessary, and I've found I do between 1 and 5 damage every hit. If you are using a dagger, it could add up, but the pros and cons are even. Blaze and Ice Spikes... okay for soloing, but you won't be taking too many hits in parties. Refresh, IMO, is a must buy. Finally, Raise, I would buy it just in the event your WHM is dead but you managed to escape. Your party will love you for that (unless you caused their untimely end in the first place). And that's all I can think of.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
